Today [17 Apr 2015], ProMED posted without critical comment a media release from the Global Alliance for Rabies Control [GARC], which claimed:

"A global study on canine rabies [20150417.3304445] published today (17 Apr 2015), has found that 160 people die every single day from the disease ... the study says that around 59 000 people die every year of rabies transmitted by dogs." These numbers were projected largely from the claim that "India has the highest number of fatalities, with over 20 000 human deaths annually." Upon what is that claim based?

There are actually just 6 mentions of India in the entire GARC paper, as published in PLOS Neglected Tropical Diseases, http://dx.plos.org/10.1371/journal.pntd.0003709. Of these mentions, only one refers to data other than abstract projections: "According to our estimates, India, the world's 2nd most populous country (with close to 18 percent of the global population) accounts for over 35 per cent of the global rabies burden (approximately 20 800 deaths). This is broadly consistent with a recent verbal autopsy study, that estimated 12 700 deaths from furious rabies alone in India."

The "verbal autopsy study" in fact projects barely half as many human rabies deaths as the GARC paper claims.

Meanwhile, this figure of 20 000-odd human rabies deaths has been kicking around for more than 100 years now, projected from the same data as commonly cited and comparably exaggerated claims for the numbers of human rabies deaths in Bangladesh and Pakistan, all of which originated with a survey of government hospitals done by David Semple and William F Harvey in 1911, at a time when India, Bangladesh, and Pakistan were all under British administration. The Semple and Harvey survey was preliminary to the introduction of post-rabies exposure vaccination to India. It was in effect the "before" study, for which the WHO-sponsored National Multicentric Rabies Survey of 2003 and the Central Bureau of Health Intelligence data collections are the "after," all of them using essentially the same methodology.

